th theorists and moving image practitioners, Cinematic Intermediality: Theory and Practice stimulates fresh thinking about how intermediality, as both a creative method and an interpretative paradigm, can be explored alongside probing questions of what cinema is, has been and can be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aIntermediality. 0aMotion pictures and the arts. 0aMotion picturesxCriticism and interpretation. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aBarber, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeugnet, Martine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDicker, Barnaby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJutz, Gabriele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnowles, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPethő, Ágnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPucill, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReynolds, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberts, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRocamora, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmid, Marion, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSchmid, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTownsend, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVasof, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiseman, Boris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb